# Field Engineer demo context

This repository prepares a **Cursor 201 Deep Dive** presentation for the Cursor Solutions Team Field Engineer interview process. The audience is a smaller, technical group (e.g. Adobe pilot users) who already know Cursor basics and want advanced workflows, tips, and tricks.

**Demo artifacts:** `.demo/` (Linear issue template, browser repro coords, BugBot setup)

## Objective

Deliver a 20-minute follow-up after a successful 101-level trial. Demonstrate technical depth, advanced capabilities, and trusted-advisor positioning — how AI coding tools should be used at scale in modern engineering organizations. Use slides, live demo, or any mix that best teaches technical workflows.

## Goals

- **Cursor 201** — Advanced topics or an end-to-end workflow; depth over breadth.
- **Workflow design** — Realistic engineering problem solved with Cursor end-to-end (rules, commands, MCP, hooks, browser automation).
- **Thought leadership** — Strategies and frameworks for how teams should use AI to build better and faster.
- **New “aha!” moments** — Creative leverage beyond feature explanations.

**Avoid:** Re-teaching Cursor 101 or speaking generically about AI without hands-on application.

## Evaluation criteria

- Advanced platform knowledge (depth in a few areas beats surface coverage of many)
- Workflow design thinking (clear, effective workflows for real team value)
- Leadership and coaching (teach others how to think about AI coding tools)
- Technical depth (models, context windows, memory, tool selection, Cursor mechanics)

## Session format

| Segment | Duration | Focus |
|---------|----------|--------|
| Live presentation & deep dive | 20 min | Present to the technical pilot group; include at least one live advanced workflow walkthrough. Conversational — pause, ask questions, check in with the “customer.” |
| Technical Q&A | 5 min | Advanced questions, objections, “how do I do X?” from power users |
| Discussion | 5 min | Role of Field Engineering in AI tooling; how AI reshapes software development teams |

## Demo workflow (this repo)

Excalidraw stands in for Adobe-style web canvas editors (hit-testing, rotation, document model). The live walkthrough fixes a seeded rotated-rectangle selection bug using:

- **Linear MCP** — fetch issue context
- **Browser automation** — reproduce and verify
- **Rules** — `.cursor/rules/` (e.g. `element-conventions.mdc`, `pr-conventions.mdc`)
- **Hooks** — `.cursor/hooks/` (e.g. block protected paths)
- **Skills** — `.cursor/skills/verify-canvas-interaction/`
- **BugBot** — PR review layer

See `DEMO-RUNBOOK.md` for minute-by-minute beats, root-cause steering notes, and Q&A prep.

## Live demo agent prompt

Paste this to start the live walkthrough:

```
We have a Linear bug report about rotated rectangles not selecting on click.
1. Fetch the Linear issue via MCP for full repro steps.
2. Start the dev server if needed and reproduce in the browser — screenshot the failure.
3. Find root cause in the hit-testing pipeline and fix it.
4. Add a Vitest regression test under packages/utils/geometry/ per project rules.
5. Run the targeted test suite and re-verify in the browser.
6. Open a PR with root cause and test plan.
Do NOT edit files under packages/excalidraw/locales/ or firebase-project/ — team policy blocks this.
```
